Date: 0/11/1831
Source: Letter
Author: BELL
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: The black whale fishery was tried in New Zealand some years ago, but it was abandoned until last year, when it was renewed by one vessel and two shore parties from Sydney, and one vessel from Hobart Town.
Notes: 1831 Nov Bell Letter in 1913 McNab Old Whaling Days 3

Date: 0/11/1831
Source: Letter
Author: BELL
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: If the fishing is to be carried on by a shore party, the try pots and huts are erected on the beach ... The boats are sent out at daylight every morning, and when ... they kill a fish it is towed ashore and flinched and boiled upon the beach.
Notes: 1831 Nov Bell Letter in 1913 McNab Old Whaling Days 9

Date: 28/4/1836
Source: Log of Mary Mitchell
Author: CAPT. JOY
Vol / Page:
Edition:
Quote: ... it was told to me by our toungers [sic, at Cloudy Bay] that the cost [of a shore-hut] was trifling. ... I was to pay the 2 [Maoris] and on the same terms as the Agent of the shore partythe other side ... Indian Cunning was plainly to be seen and as far as regards White men I fear their honesty will prove Something Equivocal.
Notes: 1836 Apr 28 Capt. Joy Log of <i>Mary Mitchell</i> in 1913 McNab Old Whaling Days 435, 436

